<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-27T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-27T20:00:00-05:00" n="111" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/804: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Castleman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-27T19:00:00-06:00">October 27, 1937—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 10:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>156. Department’s telegram No. 74. President Somoza informs me that
                                Nicaragua agrees on San José for the first stage of negotiations,
                                reserving until later date its decision regarding the venue of the
                                second stage. Will probably name two delegates, one a liberal and
                                the other a conservative, each accompanied by a counselor who will
                                not be a delegate. The President says that the delegation will be
                                ready to start negotiations in San José November 1.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Tegucigalpa.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Castleman</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>